</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Endomyocardial fibrosis (EMF) affects approximately 12 million persons worldwide and is an important cause of restrictive cardiomyopathy in the developing world, with the highest prevalence reported in sub-Saharan Africa, South Asia, and South America. EMF is characterized by apical filling with fibrotic tissue of one or both ventricles, often associated with thrombus, calcification, and atrioventricular valve regurgitation, leading to typical symptoms of restrictive heart failure. Transthoracic echocardiography (TTE) is the first-line modality for assessment of EMF, basically owing to its widespread availability. However, in recent years cardiac MRI has emerged as a powerful tool for assessment of cardiac morphology and function, with higher accuracy than TTE, along with the unique advantage of being able to provide comprehensive noninvasive tissue characterization. Delayed enhancement (DE) imaging is the cornerstone of cardiac MRI tissue characterization and allows accurate identification of myocardial fibrosis, conveying valuable additional diagnostic and prognostic information. The typical DE pattern in EMF, described as the “double V” sign, consists of a three-layered pattern of normal myocardium, thickened enhanced endomyocardium, and overlying thrombus at the apex of the affected ventricle; it has excellent correlation with histopathologic findings and plays an important role in differentiating EMF from other cardiomyopathies. Conversely, fibrous tissue deposition quantified using DE imaging, when indexed to body surface area, has been shown to be a strong independent predictor of mortality. The aim of this review is to summarize state-of-the-art applications of cardiac MRI for diagnostic and prognostic assessment of patients with suspected or confirmed EMF.</div><div role="paragraph"><i>Online supplemental material is available for this article.</i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2020</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2020190148">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2020190148">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig1.jpeg" height="2299" width="3601" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Main proposed pathogenesis theories and stages of EMF. Hallmark features of chronic EMF are presented and can be correlated with findings at gross macroscopic pathologic analysis and cardiac MRI.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig2a.jpeg" height="1166" width="1202" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Comparison between appearance of acute EMF and chronic EMF at cardiac MRI. <b>(a)</b> Delayed enhancement (DE) image (two-chamber view) in a 38-year-old man with early-stage EMF shows subtle subendocardial DE at the left ventricular (LV) apex (arrow). (<a href="#fig2a">Fig 2a</a> reprinted from reference <a href="#r15" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r15">15</a> under a CC BY-NC-ND license.) <b>(b)</b> DE image (three-chamber view) in a 27-year-old woman with chronic EMF shows marked subendocardial thickening of both ventricular apices with overlying thrombus (“double V” sign).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig2b.jpeg" height="1166" width="1343" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Comparison between appearance of acute EMF and chronic EMF at cardiac MRI. <b>(a)</b> Delayed enhancement (DE) image (two-chamber view) in a 38-year-old man with early-stage EMF shows subtle subendocardial DE at the left ventricular (LV) apex (arrow). (<a href="#fig2a">Fig 2a</a> reprinted from reference <a href="#r15" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r15">15</a> under a CC BY-NC-ND license.) <b>(b)</b> DE image (three-chamber view) in a 27-year-old woman with chronic EMF shows marked subendocardial thickening of both ventricular apices with overlying thrombus (“double V” sign).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig3a.jpeg" height="1620" width="1390" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Macroscopic pathologic findings in a 53-year-old woman with EMF who died of ventricular arrhythmia. <b>(a, b)</b> Photographs of the right ventricular (RV) inlet <b>(a)</b> and outflow tract <b>(b)</b> show endocardial fibrosis (arrows) affecting the ventricular inlet, with obliteration of the ventricular apex (yellow dotted line), but sparing the outflow tract. <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>T</i> = tricuspid valve, <i>vPu</i> = pulmonary valve. <b>(c, d)</b> Photographs of the LV inlet (c) and outflow tract <b>(d)</b> show endocardial fibrosis affecting the ventricular inlet and the papillary muscles of the mitral valve <i>(M)</i> (arrows), obliteration of the LV apex (yellow dotted line in c), and extension to the ventricular outflow tract, but sparing the aortic valve (<i>Ao</i> in d). <i>LA</i> = left atrium. (<a href="#fig3a">Fig 3</a> reprinted from reference <a href="#r18" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r18">18</a> under a CC BY 4.0 license.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig3b.jpeg" height="1615" width="1269" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Macroscopic pathologic findings in a 53-year-old woman with EMF who died of ventricular arrhythmia. <b>(a, b)</b> Photographs of the right ventricular (RV) inlet <b>(a)</b> and outflow tract <b>(b)</b> show endocardial fibrosis (arrows) affecting the ventricular inlet, with obliteration of the ventricular apex (yellow dotted line), but sparing the outflow tract. <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>T</i> = tricuspid valve, <i>vPu</i> = pulmonary valve. <b>(c, d)</b> Photographs of the LV inlet (c) and outflow tract <b>(d)</b> show endocardial fibrosis affecting the ventricular inlet and the papillary muscles of the mitral valve <i>(M)</i> (arrows), obliteration of the LV apex (yellow dotted line in c), and extension to the ventricular outflow tract, but sparing the aortic valve (<i>Ao</i> in d). <i>LA</i> = left atrium. (<a href="#fig3a">Fig 3</a> reprinted from reference <a href="#r18" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r18">18</a> under a CC BY 4.0 license.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig3c.jpeg" height="1782" width="1300" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span>. Macroscopic pathologic findings in a 53-year-old woman with EMF who died of ventricular arrhythmia. <b>(a, b)</b> Photographs of the right ventricular (RV) inlet <b>(a)</b> and outflow tract <b>(b)</b> show endocardial fibrosis (arrows) affecting the ventricular inlet, with obliteration of the ventricular apex (yellow dotted line), but sparing the outflow tract. <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>T</i> = tricuspid valve, <i>vPu</i> = pulmonary valve. <b>(c, d)</b> Photographs of the LV inlet (c) and outflow tract <b>(d)</b> show endocardial fibrosis affecting the ventricular inlet and the papillary muscles of the mitral valve <i>(M)</i> (arrows), obliteration of the LV apex (yellow dotted line in c), and extension to the ventricular outflow tract, but sparing the aortic valve (<i>Ao</i> in d). <i>LA</i> = left atrium. (<a href="#fig3a">Fig 3</a> reprinted from reference <a href="#r18" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r18">18</a> under a CC BY 4.0 license.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig3d.jpeg" height="1782" width="1355" aria-labelledby="fig3d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3d</span>. Macroscopic pathologic findings in a 53-year-old woman with EMF who died of ventricular arrhythmia. <b>(a, b)</b> Photographs of the right ventricular (RV) inlet <b>(a)</b> and outflow tract <b>(b)</b> show endocardial fibrosis (arrows) affecting the ventricular inlet, with obliteration of the ventricular apex (yellow dotted line), but sparing the outflow tract. <i>RA</i> = right atrium, <i>T</i> = tricuspid valve, <i>vPu</i> = pulmonary valve. <b>(c, d)</b> Photographs of the LV inlet (c) and outflow tract <b>(d)</b> show endocardial fibrosis affecting the ventricular inlet and the papillary muscles of the mitral valve <i>(M)</i> (arrows), obliteration of the LV apex (yellow dotted line in c), and extension to the ventricular outflow tract, but sparing the aortic valve (<i>Ao</i> in d). <i>LA</i> = left atrium. (<a href="#fig3a">Fig 3</a> reprinted from reference <a href="#r18" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r18">18</a> under a CC BY 4.0 license.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig3d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig4a.jpeg" height="1303" width="1213" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Subtypes of EMF. <b>(a)</b> Biventricular EMF in a 34-year-old man. Four-chamber view from cine imaging during diastole shows obliteration of both ventricles and dilatation of both atria. <b>(b)</b> Isolated RV EMF in a 22-year-old man. Four-chamber view from cine imaging during diastole shows obliteration of the RV apex and marked right atrial dilatation. <b>(c)</b> Isolated LV EMF in a 37-year-old woman. Four-chamber view from cine imaging during diastole shows obliteration of the LV apex and left atrial dilatation. (<a href="#fig4a">Fig 4</a> courtesy of Carlos Eduardo Rochitte, MD, PhD, University of São Paulo, São Paulo, Brazil.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig4b.jpeg" height="1303" width="1238" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Subtypes of EMF. <b>(a)</b> Biventricular EMF in a 34-year-old man. Four-chamber view from cine imaging during diastole shows obliteration of both ventricles and dilatation of both atria. <b>(b)</b> Isolated RV EMF in a 22-year-old man. Four-chamber view from cine imaging during diastole shows obliteration of the RV apex and marked right atrial dilatation. <b>(c)</b> Isolated LV EMF in a 37-year-old woman. Four-chamber view from cine imaging during diastole shows obliteration of the LV apex and left atrial dilatation. (<a href="#fig4a">Fig 4</a> courtesy of Carlos Eduardo Rochitte, MD, PhD, University of São Paulo, São Paulo, Brazil.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig4c.jpeg" height="1303" width="1249" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span>. Subtypes of EMF. <b>(a)</b> Biventricular EMF in a 34-year-old man. Four-chamber view from cine imaging during diastole shows obliteration of both ventricles and dilatation of both atria. <b>(b)</b> Isolated RV EMF in a 22-year-old man. Four-chamber view from cine imaging during diastole shows obliteration of the RV apex and marked right atrial dilatation. <b>(c)</b> Isolated LV EMF in a 37-year-old woman. Four-chamber view from cine imaging during diastole shows obliteration of the LV apex and left atrial dilatation. (<a href="#fig4a">Fig 4</a> courtesy of Carlos Eduardo Rochitte, MD, PhD, University of São Paulo, São Paulo, Brazil.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig5a.jpeg" height="1321" width="1321" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Biventricular EMF in a 27-year-old woman with recent onset of exertional dyspnea, ascites, and leg swelling, suggestive of restrictive cardiomyopathy. <b>(a)</b> Cine image shows the typical morphologic pattern of biventricular EMF: apical obliteration of both ventricles associated with enlargement of both atria during diastole. Tricuspid valve retraction can be seen (arrow) (Movie 1). <b>(b)</b> DE image shows the typical three-layered DE pattern corresponding to apical fibrous tissue deposition. The pattern consists of normal myocardium, thickened enhanced endomyocardium (representing fibrosis), and overlying thrombus (double V sign).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig5b.jpeg" height="1321" width="1324" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Biventricular EMF in a 27-year-old woman with recent onset of exertional dyspnea, ascites, and leg swelling, suggestive of restrictive cardiomyopathy. <b>(a)</b> Cine image shows the typical morphologic pattern of biventricular EMF: apical obliteration of both ventricles associated with enlargement of both atria during diastole. Tricuspid valve retraction can be seen (arrow) (Movie 1). <b>(b)</b> DE image shows the typical three-layered DE pattern corresponding to apical fibrous tissue deposition. The pattern consists of normal myocardium, thickened enhanced endomyocardium (representing fibrosis), and overlying thrombus (double V sign).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig6a.jpeg" height="998" width="1250" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. EMF in a 27-year-old man. First-pass perfusion images (four-chamber view) show typical lack of perfusion caused by an LV apical thrombus. The images are displayed in sequence, with recirculation seen in the last two images (<b>g</b> and <b>h</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig6b.jpeg" height="998" width="1214" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. EMF in a 27-year-old man. First-pass perfusion images (four-chamber view) show typical lack of perfusion caused by an LV apical thrombus. The images are displayed in sequence, with recirculation seen in the last two images (<b>g</b> and <b>h</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig6c.jpeg" height="998" width="1232" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. EMF in a 27-year-old man. First-pass perfusion images (four-chamber view) show typical lack of perfusion caused by an LV apical thrombus. The images are displayed in sequence, with recirculation seen in the last two images (<b>g</b> and <b>h</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig6d.jpeg" height="992" width="1229" aria-labelledby="fig6d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6d</span>. EMF in a 27-year-old man. First-pass perfusion images (four-chamber view) show typical lack of perfusion caused by an LV apical thrombus. The images are displayed in sequence, with recirculation seen in the last two images (<b>g</b> and <b>h</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig6d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig6e.jpeg" height="992" width="1241" aria-labelledby="fig6e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6e</span>. EMF in a 27-year-old man. First-pass perfusion images (four-chamber view) show typical lack of perfusion caused by an LV apical thrombus. The images are displayed in sequence, with recirculation seen in the last two images (<b>g</b> and <b>h</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig6e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig6f.jpeg" height="992" width="1188" aria-labelledby="fig6f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6f</span>. EMF in a 27-year-old man. First-pass perfusion images (four-chamber view) show typical lack of perfusion caused by an LV apical thrombus. The images are displayed in sequence, with recirculation seen in the last two images (<b>g</b> and <b>h</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig6f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6g" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig6g.jpeg" height="983" width="1231" aria-labelledby="fig6g" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6g</span>. EMF in a 27-year-old man. First-pass perfusion images (four-chamber view) show typical lack of perfusion caused by an LV apical thrombus. The images are displayed in sequence, with recirculation seen in the last two images (<b>g</b> and <b>h</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig6g">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6h" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig6h.jpeg" height="983" width="1211" aria-labelledby="fig6h" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6h</span>. EMF in a 27-year-old man. First-pass perfusion images (four-chamber view) show typical lack of perfusion caused by an LV apical thrombus. The images are displayed in sequence, with recirculation seen in the last two images (<b>g</b> and <b>h</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig6h">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig7a.jpeg" height="1592" width="1466" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Single V sign versus double V sign. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>RA</i> = right atrium. <b>(a)</b> Biventricular EMF in a 28-year-old woman. DE image (four-chamber view) shows subendocardial enhancement without overlying thrombus (single V sign) (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Isolated LV EMF in a 35-year-old man. DE image (four-chamber view) shows typical subendocardial enhancement with overlying thrombus (double V sign) (arrows). (<a href="#fig7a">Fig 7</a> courtesy of Carlos Eduardo Rochitte, MD, PhD, University of São Paulo, São Paulo, Brazil.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig7b.jpeg" height="1592" width="1478" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Single V sign versus double V sign. <i>LA</i> = left atrium, <i>RA</i> = right atrium. <b>(a)</b> Biventricular EMF in a 28-year-old woman. DE image (four-chamber view) shows subendocardial enhancement without overlying thrombus (single V sign) (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Isolated LV EMF in a 35-year-old man. DE image (four-chamber view) shows typical subendocardial enhancement with overlying thrombus (double V sign) (arrows). (<a href="#fig7a">Fig 7</a> courtesy of Carlos Eduardo Rochitte, MD, PhD, University of São Paulo, São Paulo, Brazil.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig8a.jpeg" height="1502" width="1480" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. LV EMF in a 65-year-old woman. The typical appearance of EMF is presented using different cardiac pulse sequences (four-chamber view). <b>(a)</b> Cine image shows apical obliteration of the LV cavity during diastole. <b>(b)</b> DE image shows the typical double V sign DE pattern. <b>(c, d)</b> T1-weighted black-blood image <b>(c)</b> and T2-weighted inversion-recovery image <b>(d)</b> show signal intensity similar to that of myocardium at the ventricular apex.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig8b.jpeg" height="1502" width="1480" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. LV EMF in a 65-year-old woman. The typical appearance of EMF is presented using different cardiac pulse sequences (four-chamber view). <b>(a)</b> Cine image shows apical obliteration of the LV cavity during diastole. <b>(b)</b> DE image shows the typical double V sign DE pattern. <b>(c, d)</b> T1-weighted black-blood image <b>(c)</b> and T2-weighted inversion-recovery image <b>(d)</b> show signal intensity similar to that of myocardium at the ventricular apex.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig8c.jpeg" height="1462" width="1465" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span>. LV EMF in a 65-year-old woman. The typical appearance of EMF is presented using different cardiac pulse sequences (four-chamber view). <b>(a)</b> Cine image shows apical obliteration of the LV cavity during diastole. <b>(b)</b> DE image shows the typical double V sign DE pattern. <b>(c, d)</b> T1-weighted black-blood image <b>(c)</b> and T2-weighted inversion-recovery image <b>(d)</b> show signal intensity similar to that of myocardium at the ventricular apex.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig8d.jpeg" height="1455" width="1459" aria-labelledby="fig8d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8d</span>. LV EMF in a 65-year-old woman. The typical appearance of EMF is presented using different cardiac pulse sequences (four-chamber view). <b>(a)</b> Cine image shows apical obliteration of the LV cavity during diastole. <b>(b)</b> DE image shows the typical double V sign DE pattern. <b>(c, d)</b> T1-weighted black-blood image <b>(c)</b> and T2-weighted inversion-recovery image <b>(d)</b> show signal intensity similar to that of myocardium at the ventricular apex.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig8d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig9a.jpeg" height="1191" width="1327" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Multimodality evaluation for comprehensive tissue characterization of apical obliteration in a 47-year-old man with EMF. <b>(a)</b> Cardiac CT image (four-chamber view) shows marked calcification of the LV apex. <b>(b)</b> DE image (four-chamber view) shows apical obliteration, which corresponds to fibrous tissue deposition with overlying calcified thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig9b.jpeg" height="1191" width="1315" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Multimodality evaluation for comprehensive tissue characterization of apical obliteration in a 47-year-old man with EMF. <b>(a)</b> Cardiac CT image (four-chamber view) shows marked calcification of the LV apex. <b>(b)</b> DE image (four-chamber view) shows apical obliteration, which corresponds to fibrous tissue deposition with overlying calcified thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig10a.jpeg" height="1044" width="1231" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Differentiation between EMF and apical HCM. <b>(a–c)</b> EMF in a 69-year-old woman. Two-chamber cine images show abrupt apical obliteration in both diastole <b>(a)</b> and systole <b>(b)</b> (Movie 1). <b>(c)</b> DE image shows the typical double V sign. <b>(d–f)</b> Apical HCM in a 41-year-old man. Two-chamber cine images show spade-shaped obliteration of the LV cavity toward the apex only during systole <b>(e)</b>, not during diastole <b>(d)</b> (Movie 2). <b>(f)</b> DE image shows the characteristic patchy enhancement in the apical segments.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig10b.jpeg" height="1044" width="1227" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Differentiation between EMF and apical HCM. <b>(a–c)</b> EMF in a 69-year-old woman. Two-chamber cine images show abrupt apical obliteration in both diastole <b>(a)</b> and systole <b>(b)</b> (Movie 1). <b>(c)</b> DE image shows the typical double V sign. <b>(d–f)</b> Apical HCM in a 41-year-old man. Two-chamber cine images show spade-shaped obliteration of the LV cavity toward the apex only during systole <b>(e)</b>, not during diastole <b>(d)</b> (Movie 2). <b>(f)</b> DE image shows the characteristic patchy enhancement in the apical segments.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig10c.jpeg" height="1044" width="1230" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span>. Differentiation between EMF and apical HCM. <b>(a–c)</b> EMF in a 69-year-old woman. Two-chamber cine images show abrupt apical obliteration in both diastole <b>(a)</b> and systole <b>(b)</b> (Movie 1). <b>(c)</b> DE image shows the typical double V sign. <b>(d–f)</b> Apical HCM in a 41-year-old man. Two-chamber cine images show spade-shaped obliteration of the LV cavity toward the apex only during systole <b>(e)</b>, not during diastole <b>(d)</b> (Movie 2). <b>(f)</b> DE image shows the characteristic patchy enhancement in the apical segments.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig10d.jpeg" height="1043" width="1240" aria-labelledby="fig10d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10d</span>. Differentiation between EMF and apical HCM. <b>(a–c)</b> EMF in a 69-year-old woman. Two-chamber cine images show abrupt apical obliteration in both diastole <b>(a)</b> and systole <b>(b)</b> (Movie 1). <b>(c)</b> DE image shows the typical double V sign. <b>(d–f)</b> Apical HCM in a 41-year-old man. Two-chamber cine images show spade-shaped obliteration of the LV cavity toward the apex only during systole <b>(e)</b>, not during diastole <b>(d)</b> (Movie 2). <b>(f)</b> DE image shows the characteristic patchy enhancement in the apical segments.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig10d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig10e.jpeg" height="1043" width="1241" aria-labelledby="fig10e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10e</span>. Differentiation between EMF and apical HCM. <b>(a–c)</b> EMF in a 69-year-old woman. Two-chamber cine images show abrupt apical obliteration in both diastole <b>(a)</b> and systole <b>(b)</b> (Movie 1). <b>(c)</b> DE image shows the typical double V sign. <b>(d–f)</b> Apical HCM in a 41-year-old man. Two-chamber cine images show spade-shaped obliteration of the LV cavity toward the apex only during systole <b>(e)</b>, not during diastole <b>(d)</b> (Movie 2). <b>(f)</b> DE image shows the characteristic patchy enhancement in the apical segments.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig10e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10f" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig10f.jpeg" height="1043" width="1224" aria-labelledby="fig10f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10f</span>. Differentiation between EMF and apical HCM. <b>(a–c)</b> EMF in a 69-year-old woman. Two-chamber cine images show abrupt apical obliteration in both diastole <b>(a)</b> and systole <b>(b)</b> (Movie 1). <b>(c)</b> DE image shows the typical double V sign. <b>(d–f)</b> Apical HCM in a 41-year-old man. Two-chamber cine images show spade-shaped obliteration of the LV cavity toward the apex only during systole <b>(e)</b>, not during diastole <b>(d)</b> (Movie 2). <b>(f)</b> DE image shows the characteristic patchy enhancement in the apical segments.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig10f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig11a.jpeg" height="1086" width="1324" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Apical thrombus. <b>(a)</b> Anterior myocardial infarction in a 37-year-old man. Four-chamber DE image shows transmural enhancement related to the left anterior descending coronary artery territory, characteristic of myocardial infarction, with a small apical thrombus. There is no obliteration of the ventricular apex. <b>(b)</b> Dilated cardiomyopathy in a 37-year-old woman with recent onset of exertional dyspnea 3 months after giving birth. Four-chamber DE image shows dilated cardiomyopathy without myocardial enhancement, suggestive of peripartum cardiomyopathy, with a large apical thrombus. There is no subendocardial enhancement between the thrombus and the myocardium, as opposed to the typical aspect of EMF.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig11b.jpeg" height="1086" width="1312" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Apical thrombus. <b>(a)</b> Anterior myocardial infarction in a 37-year-old man. Four-chamber DE image shows transmural enhancement related to the left anterior descending coronary artery territory, characteristic of myocardial infarction, with a small apical thrombus. There is no obliteration of the ventricular apex. <b>(b)</b> Dilated cardiomyopathy in a 37-year-old woman with recent onset of exertional dyspnea 3 months after giving birth. Four-chamber DE image shows dilated cardiomyopathy without myocardial enhancement, suggestive of peripartum cardiomyopathy, with a large apical thrombus. There is no subendocardial enhancement between the thrombus and the myocardium, as opposed to the typical aspect of EMF.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig12a.jpeg" height="1330" width="1314" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. LV noncompaction in a 22-year-old man referred for cardiac MRI for workup of palpitations. Cine SSFP imaging in the four-chamber <b>(a)</b> and two-chamber <b>(b)</b> views shows typical LV noncompaction cardiomyopathy, with marked trabeculae (*) producing a double-layered appearance of the myocardium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig12b.jpeg" height="1330" width="1337" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. LV noncompaction in a 22-year-old man referred for cardiac MRI for workup of palpitations. Cine SSFP imaging in the four-chamber <b>(a)</b> and two-chamber <b>(b)</b> views shows typical LV noncompaction cardiomyopathy, with marked trabeculae (*) producing a double-layered appearance of the myocardium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig13a.jpeg" height="1192" width="1337" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Cardiac amyloidosis in a 69-year-old man with exertional dyspnea. <b>(a)</b> Cine image (four-chamber view) shows a cardiac MRI appearance characteristic of cardiac amyloidosis. Although some morphologic similarities to EMF are seen (enlarged atria, pericardial and pleural effusion), no apical obliteration is present (Movie 5). <b>(b)</b> DE image (four-chamber view) shows a DE pattern markedly different from the double V sign seen in EMF, with diffuse subendocardial enhancement associated with unusually dark blood.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig13b.jpeg" height="1192" width="1312" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Cardiac amyloidosis in a 69-year-old man with exertional dyspnea. <b>(a)</b> Cine image (four-chamber view) shows a cardiac MRI appearance characteristic of cardiac amyloidosis. Although some morphologic similarities to EMF are seen (enlarged atria, pericardial and pleural effusion), no apical obliteration is present (Movie 5). <b>(b)</b> DE image (four-chamber view) shows a DE pattern markedly different from the double V sign seen in EMF, with diffuse subendocardial enhancement associated with unusually dark blood.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig14a.jpeg" height="1157" width="1259" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Lymphoma in a 25-year-old man positive for human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) infection. <b>(a)</b> Cine image shows masses (arrows) in both the LV and RV. The presence of more than one mass and their irregular outline, large size, and associated pericardial effusion (arrowheads) all suggest malignancy. <b>(b–e)</b> T1-weighted <i>(T1)</i><b> (b–d)</b> and T2-weighted <i>(T2)</i><b> (e)</b> images show that the masses (arrows) are homogeneous and isointense, a typical appearance of lymphomas, which can be a useful discriminating feature. <i>RVOT</i> in b = RV outflow tract. <b>(f)</b> DE image shows minimal contrast agent uptake by a mass (arrow). <i>LGE</i> = late gadolinium enhancement. (<a href="#fig14a">Fig 14</a> reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r46" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r46">46</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig14b.jpeg" height="1157" width="1213" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Lymphoma in a 25-year-old man positive for human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) infection. <b>(a)</b> Cine image shows masses (arrows) in both the LV and RV. The presence of more than one mass and their irregular outline, large size, and associated pericardial effusion (arrowheads) all suggest malignancy. <b>(b–e)</b> T1-weighted <i>(T1)</i><b> (b–d)</b> and T2-weighted <i>(T2)</i><b> (e)</b> images show that the masses (arrows) are homogeneous and isointense, a typical appearance of lymphomas, which can be a useful discriminating feature. <i>RVOT</i> in b = RV outflow tract. <b>(f)</b> DE image shows minimal contrast agent uptake by a mass (arrow). <i>LGE</i> = late gadolinium enhancement. (<a href="#fig14a">Fig 14</a> reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r46" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r46">46</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190148&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190148/asset/images/large/rg.2020190148.fig14c.jpeg" height="1157" width="1221" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaptio